        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>To maximise detection of the dust continuum and the CO(2-1) transition, the TDM correlator set-up mode is chosen.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>To maximise detection, and given the scales where the spectral energy distribution was pursued, we request the most compact configuration, which provides a 1.75 arcsec spatial resolution (~2.7 kpc at Malin1's distance). This configuration also provides a recoverable large angular scale which fully covers the central region of Malin1.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Since the best flux estimate one can currently derive is that of the dust continuum, and since it is a close tracer of the gas in the inter-stellar medium, the requested sensitivities are based on the continuum level. The spectral energy distribution analysis of this source (using 0.4um to 24um photometry) implies an observed flux at ~230GHz of 421uJy (at a -2sig level). Considering this flux to be smoothly spread over an area with a radius equal to the effective radius of the bulge component in Malin1 (2.9kpc, 1.85arcsec), which implies an area ~4.5 times larger than the requested synthesized beam area, the continuum level is expected to be at the 94uJy level. Since this value is already a conservative one, we request a 5sigma detection, which translates to a sensitivity of 18.8uJy.

We note that the implied integration time provides a line peak sensitivity ~2.7 times better than the deepest single dish observations toward Malin1 to date (Braine et al. 2000), but at much better resolution (11.8 arcsec with IRAM-30m versus 1.75 arcsec with ALMA). This conservative estimate adopts the line sensitivity at the central position reported by Braine et al. (2000) and assumes an homogeneous spatial brightness distribution within the IRAM-30m beam. The reported line peak is the current 3sigma upper-limit, while the line width is the same adopted by Braine et al. (2000) based on HI data (Pickering et al. 1997).</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
