    <prp:abstract>We propose to detect for the first time molecular gas (CO) in Malin 1, the icon of the low surface brightness galaxies (LSBGs) and also the largest disk galaxy so far (120 kpc diameter). Of the many LSBGs where the molecular gas has been detected so far, we can account less than a dozen of giant spiral LSBGs, with diameters about or larger than the Milky Way. In many of them the efforts have failed. The most impressive example for failed detections of molecular gas in this kind of galaxies is Malin 1, with a very diffuse giant disk (B-band SB of ~27 mag arcsec^-2). Here we request single pointing observations (band 6), toward the central region of Malin 1 with the most compact configuration (1.75 arcsec beam, or 2.7 kpc at Malin 1 distance), to trace the dust and the CO contents. The implied on-source integration time provides a line peak sensitivity 2.7 times better than the deepest single dish observations toward Malin 1 to date, but a much better resolution. Due to its extreme properties, Malin 1 will be one of the ultimate challenges ALMA will have to face. It is a galaxy which has been nearly impossible to study in the millimeter range. ALMA will hopefully change this trend.</prp:abstract>
